The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Retail boom boosts ICICI Bank profit

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 Money matters

 Mumbai, April 30: The retail banking boom has helped ICICI Bank post a 22 per cent growth in profit after tax at Rs 2,005 crore for 2004-05 against Rs 1,637 crore in the previous financial year.

 Total advances rose 46 per cent to Rs 91,405 crore compared with Rs 62,648 crore a year ago. The bank has maintained its growth momentum in the retail segment. 

 ?All our retail businesses like credit cards, home loans and auto loans are market leaders in their respective segment. We will continue to retain our focus on our retail segment,? said K. V. Kamath, managing director and CEO of ICICI Bank. 

 The bank has disbursed home loans worth Rs 18,873 crore in 2004-05. It has a credit card base of about 3.3 million cards as on March 31, 2005. 

 Retail assets constituted 61 per cent of advances and 58 per cent of customer assets. The bank?s net customer assets were at Rs 96,917 crore as on March 31. While retail loans have been a major driver, there has been a pick-up in industrial credit as well.

 Net interest income increased 43 per cent to Rs 2,839 crore from Rs 1,987 crore in 2003-04. Fee income increased 79 per cent to Rs 2,098 crore from Rs 1,175 crore. Retail assets grew 68 per cent to Rs 56,133 crore from Rs 33,424 crore. The bank now has the largest retail portfolio in India. Deposits increased 47 per cent to Rs 99,819 crore as on March 31 against Rs 68,109 crore. Net non-performing assets constituted 2.0 per cent of customer assets. 

 Profit after tax for the quarter ended March 31, rose 35 per cent to Rs 615 crore from Rs 455 crore in the corresponding previous period.

 The board has recommended a dividend of 75 per cent for 2004-05 and a special dividend of 10 per cent to mark the completion of 50 years in finance by the ICICI group. 




